##Global Stock Markets End "Black Week" , World Health Organization to the highest risk of the epidemic

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

The Fed's rescue at the end of market trading on February 28th sent a strong signal that it would cut interest rates as soon as possible. This should calm financial markets for at least a few days. Whether the market then rebounds or continues to slide depends on the course of the new coronavirus outbreak in the US and around the world

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Jin Yan, CAIJING correspondent in Washington

Editor | Susie

COVID-19, director general of the World Health Organization, announced in Geneva on February 28 that in view of the continued increase in the number of cases and countries affected by the outbreak outside China in recent days, the decision was made to raise the level of the new coronavirus outbreak from "high" to "very high" . This is the highest level of the WHO Risk Assessment.

While the initial impact of the outbreak was largely contained within China's borders, the financial markets in the United States did not react strongly. While China's efforts to contain the outbreak have been successful, the number of confirmed cases in South Korea, Japan, Italy, Iran and other countries has increased dramatically. This let us and European financial markets finally feel the impact of the disease risk, followed by a week-long cliff-like fall across the board.

South Korea's Ministry of Disease Management announced in the afternoon of February 28,571 new confirmed cases of coronavirus, breaking the 27-day record of 505 cases, a new one-day high. Iran is the only country in the Gulf region to report deaths from new coronavirus infections, and the country with the highest number of deaths outside China. Fears of a spread of the virus have severely disrupted international travel and supply chains, raising fears that the US and Eurozone economies may be heading for recession.

Stock markets around the world are still falling after falling sharply on Friday February 28th (EDT) amid fears that the outbreak will hit the global economy. European stocks fell again, with the Stoxx Europe 50 index down 3.62% at the close, Germany's DAX index down 3.86% , the U.K. FTSE 100 index down 3.18% and France's CAC 40 index down 3.38% . U.S. stocks open lower, with Dow down more than 1,000 points. By the close, the three main U.S. indexes were mixed, with the dow down 1.38% , the nasdaq up 0.01% and the S & P 500 down 0.83% .

The week of February 24-28 was the worst for U.S. stocks since the 2008 financial crisis, with all three major indexes down more than 10 percent. The Stoxx 50 in Europe fell more than 12 per cent, the FTSE 100 in London fell more than 11 per cent, the CAC 40 in Paris fell nearly 12 per cent and the DAX in Frankfurt fell more than 12 per cent.

The big three rallied strongly in late trading, with the Dow rising more than 700 points from its lows on February 28, while the Nasdaq recovered more than 3% of its losses. For the performance of the market, mark Zandi, chief economist at Moody's Analytics, told Caijing that the Fed bailed out the market at the end of trading on Friday and gave a strong signal to cut interest rates as soon as possible. This should calm financial markets for at least a few days. The market then rebounded or continued to slide, depending on the direction of the NCP epidemic.

At such a critical moment in financial markets, "The fundamentals of the U.S. economy are strong, " Fed Chairman Powell said in a Feb. 28 statement. At the same time, the risks to economic activity from the epidemic of NCP are constantly changing. The Fed is watching developments closely and their impact on the economic outlook. "We will use the tools of monetary policy to support the economy when necessary. "

Tandsey said several countries had seen interrelated developments, but most cases could still be traced to close contacts and there was no evidence of the virus spreading freely in the community. He stressed that the key to control the epidemic is to interrupt the chain of transmission of the virus. If strong action is taken to detect cases early, isolate and care patients, and track close contacts, "we still have a chance to control the virus. ".

Can the Fed save the market?

U.S. stocks opened sharply lower on Feb. 28, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average plunging more than 1,000 points early in the morning, extending a steep decline seen earlier in the week. U.S. stocks posted their worst week since the 2008 financial crisis, with the S & P 500 down 11.5 percent, the NASDAQ 10.5 percent and the Dow 12.4 percent. In February, the S & P 500 was down 8.4% , the dow 10% and the NASDAQ 6.4% .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The week of February 24-28 has been a week of heavy losses for U.S. stocks, with all three major benchmark indexes in a correction zone by Thursday's close. The S & P 500 pulled back in just six trading days, the shortest pullback in history. A correction is defined as a decline of at least 10 per cent from its recent peak but not more than 20 per cent. For both the S & P 500 and the Nasdaq, Thursday saw their biggest percentage declines since August 18,2011, and the Dow Jones Industrial Average posted their biggest percentage declines since February 5,2018.

The panic in the markets and the bearish outlook for demand caused by the outbreak are reflected not only in prices but also in Selling climax. Tmx Group, the parent company of the Toronto Exchange, announced on social media on Friday that the Toronto Exchange, the Toronto Gem and the Alpha trading system had stopped trading as a result of an order system failure. On the same day, Canada's only financial derivatives and Futures Exchange, the Montreal exchange, was closed as the Toronto Stock Exchange was closed.

Tmx Group, owner of TMX Group, explained that the Toronto Stock Exchange had suspended trading because of "technical problems" . Some market analysts said fears of a coronavirus may have triggered a panic sell-off, with trading volumes on the Toronto Stock Exchange already above the 30-day average before the suspension. More than 232 million shares changed hands on Thursday, exceeding the 30-day average of 231.1 million, according to FactSet.

Kenneth Rogoff, a former chief economist at the IMF and a professor of Economics and public policy at Harvard, said in an interview that the chances of a deep global recession were higher than at any time since the financial crisis.

As investors'fears mounted, the Fed's calls for a bail-out grew louder. Recent statements by Federal Reserve officials suggest that they do not yet believe action is necessary. However, data from the Chicago Mercantile Exchange Group showed that at noon us time on Thursday, fed Funds Rate Futures, which traders bet on the direction of Fed policy, give investors a 72 per cent chance that the Fed will cut key policy rates by 0.25 percentage points at its March 17-18 meeting. A week ago, the odds were 9% . With interest rates and inflation already low, it is believed the Fed may need to take aggressive steps to cut borrowing costs to cushion the economic impact of the COVID-19's rapid spread.

The greatest enemy is fear, rumor, and stigma

At least 48 countries and territories have so far reported cases of infection. This is not a time to panic, but a time to prepare for what is likely to be called a 'forelock' , UN Secretary General Gutterres told the press at his headquarters in New York on Thursday. The time has come for all governments to step up their efforts and do everything possible to contain the epidemic, and this should be done without humiliation and respect for human rights.

"We know we can contain the outbreak, but the window of opportunity is closing, " Gutterres said. I therefore call upon all states to assume their responsibilities and demonstrate solidarity and comprehensive global support. In doing so, all countries should have the confidence that they will have the support of the United Nations and the World Health Organization. "

Outbreaks continue to escalate in Europe and the Middle East, with Italy and Iran at the center.

As of 17:00 p.m. local time on February 28, Italy had a total of 888 confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia, the head of Italy's Civil Defense Department, David Borrelli, said in a routine notification of the disease, there were 238 more cases than the previous day. Of those, 21 died and 46 recovered. Of the confirmed cases, 412 were asymptomatic or had mild symptoms, and 64 were in intensive care, David Borrelli said. In addition, the four new deaths were all over the age of 75. At this point, a total of 13 regions and an autonomous province of Italy, a new outbreak of pneumonia.

Iran is the only country in the Gulf region to report deaths from new coronavirus infections, and the country with the highest number of deaths outside China. More than 300 cases have been confirmed in the country, including the vice president of Iran and the Deputy Minister of Health. Cases have been reported in Kuwait, Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates and Oman, among other Gulf states. Tehran has cancelled Friday prayers in the capitals of 23 provinces, including Tehran and the Shiite holy cities of Qom and Mashhad, as the outbreak spreads.

The virus is the most democratic, Feng Daxuan, a former vice president of the University of Texas at Dallas who chaired a transatlantic conference call between U.S. officials and the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention during SARS, told Caijing, it treats everyone the same. Japan and China decided on Friday February 28th to start bilateral cooperation in dealing with the new coronavirus outbreak.

To prevent the new coronavirus, the US Navy on February 28 issued a new measure, ordered all ports in the Pacific Ocean ships must be in self-isolation at sea for 14 days. "As a precaution, the Pacific Fleet is implementing a new protocol to prevent crew members from contracting the new coronavirus and to monitor crew members going to high-risk areas, " Navy spokesman Lt. James Addams said. There is no indication that any U. S. Navy personnel have been infected with the virus.
